\begin_layout Standard
A Markov chain is defined using a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $(K,{\cal A})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is the state space and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 is a set of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 that is closed under complements and countable unions.
 For each element 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, we have a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{u}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(K,{\cal A})$
\end_inset

, i.e., each set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in{\cal A}$
\end_inset

 has a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{u}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Informally, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{u}$
\end_inset

 is the distribution obtained upon taking one step from 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 The triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(K,{\cal A},\{P_{u}:u\in K\})$
\end_inset

 along with a starting distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 defines a Markov chain, i.e., a sequence of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0},w_{1},\ldots$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}$
\end_inset

 is chosen from 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 and each subsequent 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 is chosen from 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{w_{i-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 The choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 and is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0},\ldots,w_{i-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(K,{\cal A})$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
stationary
\emph default
 if taking one step from it maintains the distribution, i.e., for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in{\cal A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{K}P_{u}(A)\,dQ(u)=Q(A).
\]

\end_inset

A distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
atom-free
\emph default
 if there is no 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(x)>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
For the ball walk in a convex body, the state space 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is the convex body, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the set of all measurable subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 The next step distribution is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{u}(\{u\})=1-\frac{\vol\left(K\cap(u+\delta B_{n})\right)}{\vol(\delta B_{n})}
\]

\end_inset

and for any measurable subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{u}(A)=\frac{\vol\left(A\cap(u+\delta B_{n})\right)}{\vol(\delta B_{n})}+1_{u\in A}(u)P_{u}(\{u\})
\]

\end_inset

The uniform distribution is stationary, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(A)=\frac{\vol(A)}{\vol(K)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
ergodic flow
\emph default
 of a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 w.r.t.
 the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi(A)=\int_{A}P_{u}(K\setminus A)\,dQ(u).
\]

\end_inset

A distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is stationary if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi(A)=\Phi(K\setminus A)$
\end_inset

.
 The existence and uniqueness of the stationary distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 for general Markov chains is a subject on its own.
 One way to ensure uniqueness of a stationary distribution is to use 
\emph on
lazy
\emph default
 Markov chains.
 In a lazy version of a given Markov chain, at each step, with probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

, we do nothing; with the rest we take a step according to the Markov chain.
 The next theorem is folklore.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
If 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is stationary w.r.t.
 a lazy ergodic Markov chain, then it is the unique stationary distribution
 for that Markov chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Informally, the mixing rate of a random walk is the number of steps required
 to reduce some measure of the distance of the current distribution to the
 stationary distribution by a constant factor.
 The following notions will be useful for comparing two distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $P,Q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Total variation distance is 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{tv}(P,Q)=\sup_{A\in\mathcal{A}}|P(A)-Q(A)|.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi^{2}(P,Q)=\int_{K}\left(\frac{dP(u)}{dQ(u)}-1\right)^{2}dQ(u)=\int_{K}\left(\frac{dP(u)}{dQ(u)}\right)^{2}\,dQ(u)-1=\int_{K}\frac{dP(u)}{dQ(u)}\,dP(u)-1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Warmth: 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-warm w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\sup_{A\in\mathcal{A}}\frac{P(A)}{Q(A)}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Convergence via Conductance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we introduce an important tool to bound the rate of convergence of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{t},$
\end_inset

the distribution after 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 steps to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is the unique stationary distribution.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $conductance$
\end_inset

 of a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(A)=\frac{\Phi(A)}{\min\{Q(A),Q(K\setminus A)\}}
\]

\end_inset

and the conductance of the Markov chain is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi=\min_{A}\phi(A)=\min_{0<Q(A)\leq\frac{1}{2}}\frac{\int_{A}P_{u}(K\setminus A)\,dQ(u)}{Q(A)}.
\]

\end_inset

The 
\emph on
local
\emph default
 conductance of an element 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(u)=1-P_{u}(\{u\})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq s<\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-conductance of a Markov chain is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{s}=\min_{A:s<Q(A)\leq\frac{1}{2}}\frac{\phi(A)}{Q(A)-s}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ideally we would like to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $d(Q_{t},Q)$
\end_inset

, the distance between the distribution after 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 steps and the target 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is monotonically (and rapidly) decreasing.
 We consider 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sup_{A:Q(A)=x}Q_{t}(A)-Q(A)
\]

\end_inset

for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 To prove inductively that this quantity decreases, Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be the set of functions defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal G}_{x}=\left\{ g:K\rightarrow[0,1]\ :\ \int_{u\in K}g(u)\ dQ(u)=x\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Using this, define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{t}(x)=\sup_{g\in{\cal G}_{x}}\int_{u\in K}g(u)\ (dQ_{t}(u)-dQ(u))=\sup_{g\in{\cal G}_{x}}\int_{u\in K}g(u)\ dQ_{t}(u)-x.
\]

\end_inset

This function is strongly concave.
\end_layout

