\begin_layout Section
Conductance of the Ball Walk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the section we bound the conductance of the ball walk when applied to
 the indicator function of a convex body.
 At first glance, the ball walk is not an efficient algorithm, even for
 uniformly sampling a convex body.
 The reason is simply that the local conductance could be exponentially
 small (consider a point close to the vertex of a polyhedron).
 We can get around this in two ways.
 The first, which is simpler, but less efficient is to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smoothen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the convex body by taking the Minkowski sum with a small Euclidean ball,
 i.e., replace 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $K+\alpha B^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a convex body in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 containing the unit ball.
 Show that (a) 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol(K+\alpha B^{n})\le(1+\alpha)^{n}K$
\end_inset

 and (b) with 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\alpha/\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

 the local conductance of every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $K+\alpha B^{n}$
\end_inset

 is at least an absolute constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Using the exercise, it suffices to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1/n$
\end_inset

, so that a sample from 
\begin_inset Formula $K+\alpha B^{n}$
\end_inset

 has a large probability of being in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=1/n^{3/2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
The second approach is to show that the local conductance is in fact large
 almost everywhere, and if the starting distribution is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

warm
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 then these points can effectively be ignored.
 This will allow us to make 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 much larger, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=1/\sqrt{n}.$
\end_inset

 Larger step sizes should allows us to prove faster mixing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To convey the main ideas of the analysis, we focus on the first approach
 here.
 The goal is to show that the conductance of any subset is large, i.e., the
 probability of crossing over in one step is at least proportional to the
 measure of the set or its complement, whichever is smaller.
 First, we argue that the one-step distributions of two points will have
 a significant overlap if the points are sufficient close.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:ONESTEP"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One-step overlap
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in K$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(u),\ell(v)\ge\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\norm{u-v}\le\frac{t\delta}{\sqrt{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the one-step distributions from them satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{TV}(P_{u},P_{v})\le1+t-\ell$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=1$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the balls of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 are fully contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 The TV distance between these distributions is bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol(u+\delta B^{n}\setminus v+\delta B^{n})=\vol(v+\delta B^{n}\setminus u+\delta B^{n})$
\end_inset

 divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol(\delta B^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 This is exactly the volume of a band of thickness 
\begin_inset Formula $\norm{u-v}$
\end_inset

 centered at the center of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta B^{n}$
\end_inset

 (see Fig.
 ).
 This has relative volume at most 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, proving the lemma under the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=1$
\end_inset

.
 For the general case, we note that when the balls are intersected with
 a convex body, the increase in the TV distance is at most the probability
 that there is no proper move at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

), i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\ell$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the proof.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\ell/2$
\end_inset

, this says that if the total variation distance between the one-step distributi
ons from 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

 is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\ell/2$
\end_inset

, then the distance between them is at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell\delta}{2\sqrt{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 What this effectively says is that points close to the internal boundary
 of a subset are likely to cross over to the other side.
 To complete a proof we would need to show that the internal boundary of
 any subset is large if the subset (or its complement) is large, a purely
 geometric property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:isoD"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Isoperimetry
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1},S_{2},S_{3}$
\end_inset

 be a partition of a convex body 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vol(S_{3})\ge\frac{2}{D}d(S_{1},S_{2})\min\left\{ \vol(S_{1}),\vol(S_{2})\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be generalized to any logconcave measure.
 We will discuss this and other extensions in detail later.
 But first we bound the conductance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:ball_walk_cond"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a convex body in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 of diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 containing the unit ball and with every 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in K$
\end_inset

 having 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(u)\ge\ell.$
\end_inset

 Then the conductance of the ball walk on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with step size 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega\left(\frac{\ell^{2}\delta}{\sqrt{n}D}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=S_{1}\cup S_{2}$
\end_inset

 be a partition into measurable sets.
 We will prove that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\int_{S_{1}}P_{x}(S_{2})\,dx & \ge & \frac{\ell^{2}\delta}{16\sqrt{n}D}\min\{\vol(S_{1}),\vol(S_{2})\}\label{COND}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Note that since the uniform distribution is stationary, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S_{1}}P_{x}(S_{2})\,dx=\int_{S_{2}}P_{x}(S_{1})\,dx.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Consider the points that are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

deep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 inside these sets, i.e., unlikely to jump out of the set: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{1}'=\left\{ x\in S_{1}:P_{x}(S_{2})<\frac{\ell}{4}\right\} \mbox{ and }S_{2}'=\left\{ x\in S_{2}:P_{x}(S_{1})<\frac{\ell}{4}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}'$
\end_inset

 be the rest i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}'=K\setminus S_{1}'\setminus S_{2}'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol(S_{1}')<\vol(S_{1})/2$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S_{1}}P_{x}(S_{2})\,dx\ge\frac{\ell}{4}\vol(S_{1}\setminus S_{1}')\geq\frac{\ell}{8}\vol(S_{1})
\]

\end_inset

which proves (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "COND"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
So we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol(S_{1}')\geq\vol(S_{1})/2$
\end_inset

 and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol(S_{2}')\geq\vol(S_{2})/2$
\end_inset

.
 Now, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in S_{1}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in S_{2}'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
||P_{u}-P_{v}||_{tv}\geq1-P_{u}(S_{2})-P_{v}(S_{1})>1-\frac{\ell}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Applying Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:ONESTEP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\ell/2$
\end_inset

, we get that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|u-v|\geq\frac{\ell\delta}{2\sqrt{n}}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $d(S_{1},S_{2})\geq\ell\delta/2\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Applying Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:isoD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}',S_{2}',S_{3}'$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vol(S_{3}') & \geq & \frac{\ell\delta}{\sqrt{n}D}\min\{\vol(S_{1}'),\vol(S_{2}')\}\\
 & \geq & \frac{\ell\delta}{2\sqrt{n}D}\min\{\vol(S_{1}),\vol(S_{2})\}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We can now prove (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "COND"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{S_{1}}P_{x}(S_{2})\,dx & = & \frac{1}{2}\int_{S_{1}}P_{x}(S_{2})\,dx+\frac{1}{2}\int_{S_{2}}P_{x}(S_{1})\,dx\\
 & \ge & \frac{1}{2}\vol(S_{3}')\frac{\ell}{4}\\
 & \ge & \frac{\ell^{2}\delta}{16\sqrt{n}D}\min\{\vol(S_{1}),\vol(S_{2})\}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
The ball walk in a convex body with local conductance at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 everywhere has mixing rate 
\begin_inset Formula $O(nD^{2}\delta^{2}/\ell^{4})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the construction above of adding a small ball to every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 gives a lower bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=1/n^{3/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=\Omega(1)$
\end_inset

 and thus a polynomial bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n^{4}D^{2})$
\end_inset

 on the mixing time.
 As we will see presently, this can be improved to 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}D^{2}$
\end_inset

 by avoiding the blow-up, and analyzing the 
\emph on
average 
\emph default
local conductance.
 The example of starting near a corner (say of a hypercube) shows that this
 cannot work in general; however, from a 
\emph on
warm
\emph default
 start, it will suffice to bound the average local conductance rather than
 the minimum.
 
\end_layout

