\begin_layout Subsection*
Tightness of the bound
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mixing rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n^{2}D^{2})$
\end_inset

 for the ball walk is in fact the best possible even from a warm start (with
 the assumption of a unit ball inside the convex body and diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

).
 To see this, consider a cylinder whose cross-section is a unit ball and
 axis is 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,D]$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose the starting distribution is uniform in the part of the cylinder
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,D/3]$
\end_inset

.
 Then we claim that to reach the opposite third of the cylinder needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(n^{2}D^{2})$
\end_inset

 steps with high probability.
 Each step has length at most 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 in a random direction, and this is about 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta/\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1}$
\end_inset

.
