\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
For any partition 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1},S_{2},S_{3}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n}$
\end_inset

, and any logconcave measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu(S_{3})\ge\frac{\ln2}{\E_{\mu}(\norm{x-\bar{x}})}\min\left\{ \mu(S_{1}),\mu(S_{2})\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, for a (near-)isotropic distribution, the diameter can be replaced
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\sqrt{n})$
\end_inset

 and this gives a bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n^{3})$
\end_inset

 from a warm start.
 One way to summarize the analysis so far is that the complexity of sampling
 a convex body (and in fact a logconcave density) from a warm start is 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{*}(n^{2}/\psi^{2})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is the isoperimetric ratio of the convex body.
 In other words, the expansion of the Markov chain reduces to the expansion
 of the target logconcave density.
 It then becomes a natural question to find the best possible estimate for
 the isoperimetric ratio.
 KLS also provided a conjecture for this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Conjecture
The isoperimetric ratio of any isotropic logconcave density in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bound of the conjecture holds for all halfspace induced subsets.
 So the conjecture says that the worst isoperimetry is achieved up to a
 constant factor by a halfspace (this version does not need isotropic position).
 Here we discuss a powerful technique for proving such inequalities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classical proofs of isoperimetry for special distributions are based on
