\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $H'$
\end_inset

.
 Since this is a continuous family, there must be a halfspace for which
 the function is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If we take all 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-2)$
\end_inset

-dimensional affine subspaces defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x\in\Rn:\ x_{i}=r_{1},\,x_{j}=r_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},r_{2}$
\end_inset

 are rational, then the intersection of all the corresponding bisecting
 halfspaces is a line or a point (by choosing only rational values for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

, we are considering a countable intersection).
 To see why it is a line or a point, assume we are left with a two or higher
 dimensional set.
 Since the intersection is convex, there is a point in its interior with
 at least two coordinates that are rational, say 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=r_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 But then there is a bisecting halfspace 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 that contains the affine subspace given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=r_{1},\,x_{2}=r_{2}$
\end_inset

 in its boundary, and so it properly partitions the current set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Thus the limit of this bisection process is a function supported on an interval
 (which could be a single point), and since the function itself is a limit
 of convex sets (intersections of halfspaces) containing this interval,
 it is a limit of a sequence of concave functions and is itself concave,
 with positive integrals.
 Simplifying further from concave to linear takes quite a bit of work.
 For the full proof, we refer the reader to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LS93"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Going back to the proof sketch of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "ISO2"

\end_inset

, we can apply the localization lemma to get an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 and an affine function 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{1}\ell(t)^{n-1}g((1-t)a+tb)\,dt>0\quad\mbox{ and }\quad\int_{0}^{1}\ell(t)^{n-1}h((1-t)a+tb)\,dt>0.\label{AFTERLEMMA}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h$
\end_inset

 as we have defined them are not lower semi-continuous.
 However, this can be addressed by expanding 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

 slightly so as to make them open sets, and making the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 an open set.
 Since we are proving strict inequalities, these modifications do not affect
 the conclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us partition 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1},Z_{2},Z_{3}$
\end_inset

 as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{i}=\{t\in[0,1]\,:\,(1-t)a+tb\in S_{i}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that for any pair of points 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in Z_{1},v\in Z_{2},\,|u-v|\ge d(S_{1},S_{2})/D$
\end_inset

.
 We can rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "AFTERLEMMA"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{Z_{3}}\ell(t)^{n-1}f((1-t)a+tb)\,dt<C\int_{Z_{1}}\ell(t)^{n-1}f((1-t)a+tb)\,dt
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{Z_{3}}\ell(t)^{n-1}f((1-t)a+tb)\,dt<C\int_{Z_{2}}\ell(t)^{n-1}f((1-t)a+tb)\,dt.
\]

\end_inset

The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(\cdot)^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 are both logconcave, so 
\begin_inset Formula $F(t)=\ell(t)^{n-1}f((1-t)a+tb)$
\end_inset

 is also logconcave.
 We get, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{Z_{3}}F(t)\,dt<C\min\left\{ \int_{Z_{1}}F(t)\,dt,\int_{Z_{2}}F(t)\,dt\right\} .\label{FEQ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now consider what Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "ISO2"

\end_inset

 asserts for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(t)$
\end_inset

 over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1},Z_{2},Z_{3}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{Z_{3}}F(t)\,dt\geq2d(Z_{1},Z_{2})\min\left\{ \int_{Z_{1}}F(t)\,dt,\int_{Z_{2}}F(t)\,dt\right\} .\label{FEQ2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We have substituted 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 for the diameter of the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $2d(Z_{1},Z_{2})\geq2d(S_{1},S_{2})/D=C$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "ISO2"

\end_inset

 applied to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(t)$
\end_inset

 contradicts 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "FEQ"

\end_inset

 and to prove the theorem in general, and it suffices to prove it in the
 one-dimensional case.
 A combinatorial argument reduces this to the case when each 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a single interval.
 Proving the resulting inequality up to a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is a simple exercise and uses only the unimodality of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The improvement to the tight bound requires one-dimensional logconcavity.
 This completes the proof of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "ISO2"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

